<h3>Best Solar Panel Types for Washington</h3>
<p>Given Washington's frequently overcast conditions, monocrystalline solar panels are typically the best choice for residential installations. These panels perform better in low-light conditions compared to polycrystalline alternatives and maintain higher efficiency rates throughout their lifespan. Premium manufacturers like SunPower, LG, and Panasonic offer panels with efficiency ratings exceeding 20%, which is particularly valuable in Washington where maximizing production per square foot is important.</p>

<p>For homeowners with larger roof areas and budget constraints, high-quality polycrystalline panels from manufacturers like Canadian Solar or Trina Solar can provide excellent value. These panels typically cost 10-15% less than monocrystalline options while still delivering reliable performance in Washington's climate. The key is selecting panels with strong low-light performance ratings and comprehensive warranties that protect against the region's occasional severe weather.</p>

<h2>HVAC Systems in Washington</h2>

<h3>Climate Considerations</h3>
<p>Washington's climate varies dramatically from the mild, wet winters of the Puget Sound region to the more extreme seasonal variations found in eastern Washington. The marine climate of western Washington features moderate temperatures year-round, with average winter lows around 37¬∞F and summer highs reaching 75¬∞F. This climate is ideal for heat pump systems, which can provide both heating and cooling efficiently in moderate temperature ranges.</p>

<p>Eastern Washington experiences a continental climate with colder winters and warmer summers, requiring HVAC systems capable of handling temperature extremes ranging from below 20¬∞F in winter to over 90¬∞F in summer. The low humidity throughout most of the state means that cooling loads are generally lower than in more humid regions, allowing for smaller, more efficient cooling systems.</p>

<p>The state's focus on energy efficiency and environmental protection has led to increasingly stringent building codes and energy standards. Washington State Energy Code requires high-performance insulation and air sealing, which reduces HVAC loads and allows for smaller, more efficient systems. This regulatory environment makes investing in high-efficiency HVAC equipment more cost-effective due to reduced operational costs.</p>

